         <div>
            <head>22.5.1884 Donnerstag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49069">Hamburg</placeName>. May 22. 1884. Ascenscionday.
               Thursday.</p>
            <p>Received a letter from <persName key="362">Bonnemamman</persName> this morning. She is better I am glad to see. Went to Teufelsbrück in the
               afternoon. Started from here at about three. Drove to the Georgsplatz and from there
               walked to the harbour, where we took a small steamer. Saw the &#x201e;Paradox&#x201c; the ship
                  <persName key="1156">Robert</persName>
               <note type="reg">Blümer</note> is to sail in
               on the way to Teufelsbrück. In Teufelsbrück we went to a restaurant and sat out on
               the terrace. Afterwards I walked a little with <persName key="1156">Robert</persName>
               and <persName key="1157">Martin</persName>
               <note type="reg">Blümer</note>. We started
               from Teufelsbrück at six and got out at the Landungsbrücke in <placeName key="57244">S<hi rend="ul.2">
                     <hi rend="sup">t</hi>
                  </hi> Pauli</placeName>; We walked home through the hafen. I in vain looked for
               the shop with the elegant inscription &#x201e;Hospital for broken pipes&#x201c; which I saw last
               time I was there, with <persName key="4804">Paul</persName>
               <note type="reg">Blümer</note>. On the whole I spent a very pleasant day. I finished <persName key="1199">Gibbons</persName>
               <name type="work" key="28474">Memoirs</name> today, and very interstíng they are; but
               I think some of all that long writing and rewriting about the sale of his house at
                  <placeName key="49489">Beriton</placeName> and about his money matters might have
               been omitted, as there really is no earthly interest in it for any living, breathing
               human being. I read <persName key="8186">Macaulay&#x2019;s</persName>
               <name type="work" key="28475">essay on history</name> afterwards. Such an historian
               as he describes would indeed be a great historian. How I wish I could be such a one.
               The history of England so written would be the most intersting historical work in the
               world, I should think.</p>
         </div>
